## Voice and tone

- Spectrum uses a single product voice built on three principles ([voice and tone](https://spectrum.adobe.com/page/voice-and-tone/)):
  - **Rational** ‚Äì clear, understandable language, backed by research; avoid trendy or opinionated wording.
  - **Friendly** ‚Äì honest, responsible; vary sentence structure and acknowledge user emotions.
  - **Focused** ‚Äì concise and simple; only name new concepts when necessary.
- Tone moves along a documented spectrum. Match the user‚Äôs context and risk level to these attitudes:

| Tone         | Attitude & behaviors                          | Use cases                                    | Example phrase                                   |
| ------------ | --------------------------------------------- | -------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------ |
| Motivational | Positive, encouraging, celebratory            | Achievements, milestones, first-time success | "Great job! You've successfully published..."    |
| Helpful      | Polite, respectful, efficient                 | General assistance, tooltips, guidance       | "To get started, select a template..."           |
| Instructive  | Neutral, direct, step-based                   | Tutorials, how-tos, form instructions        | "Enter your email address, then click Next."     |
| Reassuring   | Professional, reliable, calming               | Processing, loading, temporary issues        | "This may take a moment. We'll notify you..."    |
| Supportive   | Concerned, empathetic, guiding through issues | Errors, failures, data loss prevention       | "We couldn't save your changes. Let's fix this." |

Pick the position (or adjacent blend) that fits the moment, and stay consistent within a flow.

### Tone selection decision tree

```
If critical error/data loss risk ‚Üí Supportive tone
If routine task/instruction ‚Üí Instructive tone
If achievement/success ‚Üí Motivational tone
If waiting/processing ‚Üí Reassuring tone
If general interaction ‚Üí Helpful tone
```

## Grammar and mechanics

Follow the full [grammar and mechanics](https://spectrum.adobe.com/page/grammar-and-mechanics/) reference:

- **Style baseline**
  - **[HIGH PRIORITY]** Sentence case for nearly everything; title case only for official names. Avoid all caps except for acronyms or required file extensions.
  - **[HIGH PRIORITY]** Default to AP style unless a component spec says otherwise.
  - **[HIGH PRIORITY]** Prefer active voice; reserve passive voice for softening sensitive notices.
  - **[HIGH PRIORITY]** Address users in second person. Use first person only when the interface is quoting the user, and rely on singular they whenever gender is unknown.
  - **[HIGH PRIORITY]** Avoid using punctuation as decoration or as a substitute for words. Skip emoji, ampersands, plus signs, slashes, and exclamation points in UI strings.
  - **[MEDIUM PRIORITY]** Use simple verb tenses so content is concise, scannable, and easier to localize.
  - **[MEDIUM PRIORITY]** Use common contractions (you're, we'll, it's) to stay conversational.
- **Punctuation**

  - **[MEDIUM PRIORITY]** Use serial commas.
  - **[LOW PRIORITY]** Use colons to introduce lists, em dashes (with spaces) for related thoughts, en dashes for ranges, smart quotation marks for quoted text or asset names, and parentheses for supplementary info.

  ### Common patterns to avoid

  ```
  Avoid: /!+/ (exclamation points)
  Avoid: /[&+]/ (ampersands, plus signs as conjunctions)
  Avoid: /:\)|\(:|üòä|üëç|‚ù§Ô∏è/ (emoticons/emojis)
  Avoid: /\.{2,}/ (ellipses for trailing off)
  ```

- **Abbreviations, numbers, dates, and times**
  - Use K/M/B for thousands, millions, billions, with a space between the number and unit (e.g., 71 M records).
  - Spell out zero through nine in running copy; use numerals for 10+, currency, timestamps, and measurements. Insert commas in large numbers.
  - Follow Spectrum‚Äôs recommendations for relative, elapsed, and remaining time labels, HH:MM:SS timestamps, and plain-language time zones (convert to the user‚Äôs zone when possible).
- **Lists**
  - Introduce lists with a phrase plus colon, keep entries parallel, capitalize the first word, and choose bullets for unordered ideas or numerals for sequences.

## Inclusive UX writing

The [inclusive UX writing overview](https://spectrum.adobe.com/page/inclusive-ux-writing/) explains why inclusion is a business, brand, and accessibility imperative.

- Tie language decisions to accessibility standards (WCAG, WAI-ARIA) and collaborate with design so the entire experience‚Äînot only the copy‚Äîis inclusive.
- Use the page as a hub: it links to detailed sub-guides (writing about people, readability, visuals) and provides external resources (NCDJ, Conscious Style Guide, 18F, etc.) that should inform decisions.
- Highlight the risks of non-inclusive language when making product choices: it limits reach, damages perception, and hinders hiring and retention.

## Writing about people

Spectrum‚Äôs [people guidance](https://spectrum.adobe.com/page/writing-about-people/) centers compassion, specificity, and respect.

- Lead with people, not conditions or labels, and include traits only when they matter to the task.
- Choose terminology with historical awareness. Avoid appropriating language from marginalized communities, and do not rely on stereotypes or proxy statements (e.g., assuming financial means).
- Be transparent about why sensitive information is collected, allow custom responses, and consider downstream use in machine learning systems.
- Apply the identity-specific sections:
  - **Disability** ‚Äì use neutral descriptors, avoid metaphors that equate disability with negative traits, and portray more types of people as typical.
  - **Race and class** ‚Äì be precise about ethnicity or region, avoid idioms with racist origins, and design/write so all cultures appear as common.
  - **Gender and sexuality** ‚Äì default to gender-neutral wording, distinguish sex vs. gender, only ask for data when essential, and teach AI systems about global identities.

## Writing for readability

The [readability guidance](https://spectrum.adobe.com/page/writing-for-readability/) focuses on helping the widest range of people succeed.

- Write for roughly a sixth-grade reading level; test content with readability tools and revise when it trends higher.
- Choose plain, globally recognizable words. Avoid internal jargon or slang unless you explain it on first use, and skip idioms entirely.
- Organize content deliberately:
  - **Layout** ‚Äì left-align running text (mirrors for RTL), avoid full justification, and rely on spacing over decorative dividers.
  - **Grammar and mechanics** ‚Äì sentence case and consistent punctuation improve scanning.
  - **Interactions** ‚Äì prevent destructive actions (avoid Clear/Reset), allow saving, and use progressive disclosure to limit cognitive load.
  - **Localization** ‚Äì explain branded or technical terms, spell out acronyms on first use, and plan for text expansion.

## Writing with visuals

Per [writing with visuals](https://spectrum.adobe.com/page/writing-with-visuals/):

- Do not rely on visuals, color, or icons to carry meaning. Describe actions, outcomes, and tasks in text.
- Avoid directional language (left, right, above). Structure instructions chronologically or by task steps instead.
- Prevent errors by using predictable labels and consistent navigation patterns.
- Minimize new naming. Every coined term adds cognitive load; reuse existing names unless a new one is absolutely required.
- Provide purposeful alt text. Follow Spectrum‚Äôs patterns for photographs, UI imagery, instructional graphics, and decorative assets (mark decorative images so assistive tech skips them). Supply captions or transcripts for audio/video assets.

## In-product word list

- The [in-product word list](https://spectrum.adobe.com/page/in-product-word-list/) is a living glossary of preferred and avoided terms.
- Always check the table for canonical wording, capitalization, spacing, and usage notes before writing new copy or coining terms.
- Favor action verbs such as Create, Share, and Export; avoid vague alternatives unless the glossary explicitly allows them.
- Use the same wording across UI, docs, and education materials so users build reliable recognition (and localization teams can reuse translations).

## Writing for errors

Adopt the full [error guidelines](https://spectrum.adobe.com/page/writing-for-errors/):

- **Prevent first** ‚Äì design flows that eliminate or auto-resolve errors whenever possible.
- **Pick the right component** ‚Äì align alert dialogs, banners, inline alerts, help text, and toasts with their documented consequence/complication/action levels.
- **Structure** ‚Äì when space allows, cover what happened, the underlying cause (if helpful), and how to fix it or what the product is doing.
- **Voice and tone** ‚Äì keep messages rational, and focused; use plain language, never blame the user, and apologize only when the system truly caused harm.
- **Specific yet reusable** ‚Äì tailor content to the scenario but use generic, localizable phrasing. Include error codes only if the audience can act on them.

### Component mapping for messages

```
- Critical errors (data loss, security) ‚Üí AlertDialog with variant="destructive"
- Success messages ‚Üí Toast with variant="positive"
- Warnings ‚Üí InlineAlert with variant="notice"
- Info/tips ‚Üí InlineAlert with variant="informative"
- Field validation ‚Üí Built-in errorMessage prop on form components
- System status ‚Üí Banner at page level
```

